    {
      "id": "986ee69a_2b463e0c",
      "file_path": "ansible/roles/nfs/molecule/default/cleanup.yml",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": null,
      "message": "I'm not pretty sure that 'cleanup.yml' should be your place of choice for those tasks. Quoting upstream docs: \n\n\"The cleanup playbook is for cleaning up test infrastructure that may not be present on the instance that will be destroyed. The primary use-case is for “cleaning up” changes that were made outside of Molecule’s test environment.\"\n\nI'd rather pick destroy.yml for that.  You're playing on 'all' hosts which are molecule created hosts, which conflicts with the beforementioned manual excerpt.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5097,
        "name": "Bartek Grzybowski",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "b.grzybowski@partner.samsung.com",
        "username": "bgrzybowski"
      },
      "updated": "2019-04-09 13:54:33.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0d7ea319_46019918",
      "file_path": "ansible/roles/nfs/molecule/default/molecule.yml",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 45,
      "message": "While i'm aware that using both: symlinking and directly defined vars here is unsupported, i'm not convinced if you can't still use symlinks for group_vars and directly defined in inventory.hosts.<host> key host variables. Have tried that? It would look nicer to have the vars here and not in separate default/host_vars dir.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5097,
        "name": "Bartek Grzybowski",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "b.grzybowski@partner.samsung.com",
        "username": "bgrzybowski"
      },
      "updated": "2019-04-09 14:02:11.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "9d5b336c_db97b163",
      "file_path": "ansible/roles/nfs/molecule/default/cleanup.yml",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": null,
      "message": "Well, destroy.yml is described as something that runs outside of the hosts, because it is destroying them.\nSo I couldn't unmount anything from there. cleanup.yml was described in an unclear way and this description really suggests it is also running outside. However, it is opposed to the prepare.yml playbook, and prepare.yml is running inside, so I assumed this one also is. I believe i am correct.\nAlso note destroy.yml is provided by molecule and cannot be... \"subclassed\".",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5019,
        "name": "Michal Zegan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
        "username": "m.zegan"
      },
      "updated": "2019-04-09 15:15:39.000000000",
